Introduction

In recent times, the United Kingdom has faced an unprecedented surge in energy price inflation, sending shockwaves through households and the broader economy. As the cost of energy continues its relentless ascent, the UK finds itself grappling with a profound cost of living crisis. This analysis aims to shed light on the consequences and subsequent indirect impacts of this energy price surge, exploring its far-reaching effects on other economic sectors in comparison to G7 countries. Ultimately, this independent analysis will arrive at an informed conclusion that can guide policy changes to aid in alleviating the burdens faced by the UKâ€™s residents through this crisis.

Consumer Price Index Inflation

Since the pandemic, the cost of living crisis has become an increasingly worrying issue for the general public. In order to understand why this has been the case, it is first vital to evaluate the reason for this current inflation wave. The last two years have seen a dramatic increase in CPI of approximately 18%. In contrast to this, during the eight year period prior to the COVID-19 pandemic, inflation was on average held slightly below the Bank of Englandâ€™s inflation targets of 2% - totaling 14% over that whole period. This alarming but predictable outcome was similarly experienced in other major G7 countries.

Figure 1 below illustrates the aforementioned increase in price level across the G7, utilising a base index of 100 at 2019. Data was obtained from ONS: Food and energy price inflation, UK:2023

Within other G7 countries, there is some evidence to believe that the signs of inflation is beginning to fall. However, there is little evidence for this in the UK. The impact of energy inflation within this model is currently unclear, in order to see the part that energy inflation plays in this cost of living crisis, we can hone in on this factor across the last year.

Energy Inflation

The UK annual energy price inflation is evident. Among G7 countries, the UK has the highest inflation rate at 40.5% in comparison to mostly low single digit - and sometimes now negative - inflation rates.

Figure 2 outlines this major discrepancy through a direct comparison of 12-month rates of energy inflation between January 2018 and March 2023. Data was obtained from ONS: Food and energy price inflation, UK:2023

Since 2019, energy prices are up by a cumulative 69% in the UK, 63% in Italy, 47% in Germany, 37% in France, 30% in the US, 25% in Canada, and 10% in Japan. This does not however paint the full picture, European countries experienced a vastly different rise in gas prices in comparison to non-European countries. In the UK alone, the nation saw a quadrupling price of gas in the 2021. Despite Ofgem price capping effects, the cost of living impact was drastic, with an Energy Price Guarantee (EPG) being introduced in October 2022 at Â£2500 to aid households during the most turbulent period.

Goods and Services

Energy inflation is not the only factor effecting the cost of living crisis however, many goods and services are having a substantial impact on the cost of living crisis too. As energy prices increase, it is only natural to assume that the higher costs for businesses would funnel down to higher prices for consumers. In order to investigate this relationship between energy price rises and goods and services further, CPI inflation rates of a variety of classes of goods and services are illustrated in figure 3 below to show how they specifically contribute to the crisis.

Data was obtained from ONS: Food and energy price inflation, UK:2023

Over 70% of these 85 items have experience record high CPI inflation rates. The worst of which being food and transport. The annual inflation rate for many food items is in the double digits, exceeding 20-25% in cases such as milk, cheese and eggs. This suggests that some non-energy items are likely being led by the higher energy prices due to the links between their sectors. The exact relationship of which is explored further in the next section.

Energy Intensity: Division Level

Due to the conclusion of the previous figureâ€™s analysis a more detailed understanding of the relationship being an economic sectorâ€™s CPI inflation and its link to the energy sector is required. The energy intensity of various major divisions, excluding the direct effects of energy, is explored in Figure 4 below.

Data was obtained from ONS: The energy intensity of the Consumer Prices Index: 2022

Clearly, the energy intensity for housing and household service (20.5%) - which does include gas electricity and liquid fuels - and transport (17.5%) which does includes fuels and lubricants are the highest unsurprisingly. If we remove fuels and lubricants, the remainder of transport has an energy intensity of 2.7%, reflecting the relatively high energy intensity of other transport products.Household services follow a similar pattern, without the energy components the housing and household services division has an energy intensity of only 1.2%. This thoroughly conveys that the higher the energy intensity of an economic sector, strongly correlates to the sectorâ€™s CPI inflation.

Contributions to CPI by Energy Intensity

To further consolidate the link between energy intensity and CPI inflation in non-direct energy sectors, figure 5 shows the breakdown of high and low energy intensity consumer goods and services from 2018-2023.

Data was obtained from ONS: The energy intensity of the Consumer Prices Index: 2022 This details that those goods and services with higher energy intensity are making the largest contribution to inflation (bar the direct energy price hikes). Besides the direct energy components,the high energy intensity components have made the largest contribution to the 12-month CPI inflation rate in the last 8 months, as higher energy prices have pushed up the costs and prices for these components the most. Isolating the last 12 months from February 2022-23, CPI inflation was 10.4%, of which 33% was from direct energy effects, 20% from very high energy intensity goods and services and a further 25% from high energy intensity.

Conclusive Policy Recommendation

This independent analysis clearly conveys the emphasis on the direct energy components and their vital role in the Consumer Price Index inflation and therefore in turn, the cost of living crisis. As a vast percentage of the current inflation crisis in the UK can be traced back to this, my policy recommendation is to focus most government aid schemes and resources to limiting the price of energy for businesses and households. Government aid schemes like the Energy Price Guarantee would have a substantial impact on bringing the inflation levels down to an acceptable rate which would help hugely with the cost of living crisis and therefore be a great incentive for public spending to increase, helping to stabilise the economy.
